    <body>
      <head>Hans Delmonte</head>
      <div>

        <p>Son of Nathan (Peter) Delmonte (1861–) and Olga (<hi rend="italic">née</hi> Israel)
          (1874–) of the Hamburg banking house N. Delmonte &amp; Co, founded 1893; husband of <ref
            cRef="entity-008445">Hedda Glässner</ref>, daughter of <ref cRef="entity-008446">Theodor
            Glässner</ref> and <ref cRef="entity-003245">Frieda (<hi rend="italic">née</hi>
            Schiff)</ref>, thus niece of <ref cRef="entity-000771">Jeanette Schenker (<hi
              rend="italic">née</hi> Schiff)</ref> and after 1919 also of <ref cRef="entity-000632"
            >Heinrich Schenker</ref>. Hedda and Hans had two children, Heinz Georg (1923–1997), and
          Gert (b. 1925).</p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <p>Hans Delmonte, presumably working for the family firm, established a fish canning factory
          in <ref cRef="entity-002248">Ústí nad Labem (Aussig an der Elbe)</ref> in May 1935. In
          that year, he and Hedda were living in <ref cRef="entity-002501">Berlin</ref>, but by
          April 1938 the family was living in Lisbon, from where they emigrated to <ref
            cRef="entity-006588">Brazil</ref>, settling in Rio de Janeiro.</p>
      </div>

    </body>

